<HL>
   Brazil's Trade Surplus Shrinks
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   RIO DE JANEIRO -- Rising oil imports caused Brazil's trade
surplus to shrink to $1.03 billion in August, down 29% from a
year ago, the government's Foreign Trade Department said.
   Exports in August were practically unchanged from July but
down 9% from a year earlier. Imports rose 23% from the
previous month and were 5% higher than in August 1989.
</LP>
