   Business Brief -- Boeing Co.:
   Unit Gets Order for Planes
   From Dutch Firm's Division
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP BA I.AER F.ASP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Boeing Co. said its de Havilland unit received an order
valued at about $22 million for two Dash 8 series 300
airplanes from Schreiner Airways B.V., a division of
Schreiner Aviation Group of the Netherlands.
   The twin-engine turboprop planes will be delivered within
the next few months, Boeing said. Schreiner Airways provides
regional commuter service, charter service and other aviation
services.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Boeing continues to discuss the possible sale of the de
Havilland unit with Aeritalia of Italy and Aerospatiale of
France. A team from the two potential buyers is expected to
continue reviewing de Havilland's operations for another few
weeks, said a de Havilland spokesman in Toronto. Boeing is
based in Seattle.
