<HL>
   R.H. Macy Is Planning to Buy Back
   Junk Bonds at Discount, Executive Says
   ----
   By George Anders
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   MZ GE LTR
</CO>
<IN>
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A top R.H. Macy &amp; Co. executive said the
retailer has drafted plans to buy back sizable amounts of its
junk bonds, which have sunk in recent weeks.
   A big bond buy-back, at a hefty discount from face value,
could significantly cut Macy's $600 million annual cash
interest bill on its $5.8 billion in debt. Likely sources of
money for an open-market bond repurchase are bank loans and
the possible sale of as much as a 20% equity stake in Macy.
If the retailer carries out its plans, that will almost
certainly be seen as upbeat news in the financial community.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bond analysts and traders have grown increasingly worried
about Macy's financial health in the past month, amid signs
that U.S. retail sales are slumping. The company's 14.5%
bonds of 1998 currently trade at 54 cents on the dollar, and
lion annual cash interest bill on its $5.8 billion in debt.
Likely sources of money for an open-market bond repurchase
are bank loans and the possible sale of as much as a 20%
equity stake in Macy. If the retailer carries out its plans,
that will almost certainly be seen as upbeat news in the
other Macy issues are even lower.
   Macy executive vice president Myron Ullman said in an
interview that the company is looking at "five or six"
different ways to finance a big bond repurchase. Mr. Ullman
said Macy directors, at a board meeting Monday, were shown an
extensive roadmap for how the company could buy large amounts
of its bonds.
   Macy has about $1.6 billion face value of junk bonds
outstanding. They were issued soon after the retailer was
taken private in a 1986 leveraged buy-out.
   This summer, Macy sold a token 1% equity stake to a real
estate developer for $15 million. Macy used part of the
proceeds to retire $45 million face value of its 16.5%
discount bonds of 2006, which traded then at about 20 cents
on the dollar, Mr. Ullman said. Macy also bought about $5
million of its 14.5% bonds of 2001, which were trading at
about 45 cents on the dollar.
   Macy wants to retire more junk bonds the same way, Mr.
Ullman said. "This is a great opportunity," he asserted. "We
never dreamed we would have the opportunity to buy bonds at
such a discount."
   Macy, though, could face a tough time lining up financing.
The company's two lead banks, Manufacturers Hanover Corp. and
Bankers Trust New York Corp., recently lent money for a
comparable bond-repurchase program by RJR Nabisco Inc., but
did so only after long negotiations and the payment of
unusually high loan fees.
   Macy's other likely source of cash is a sizable equity
infusion. The company's owners include such deep-pocketed
companies and individuals as General Electric Co., with a
20.2% stake; Loews Corp., with a 12.1% stake; Mutual Shares
Corp., with a 12.1% stake, and developer Alfred Taubman, with
a 4.1% stake.
   Mr. Ullman reaffirmed that Macy would consider selling a
20% stake in the company for $300 million. That price -- five
times what Macy's original equity investors paid in 1986 --
is in line with the company's asking price in previous talks
with potential buyers. It is unclear, though, whether a new
or existing investor would pay that much.
   Last week, several junk-bond analysts cut their estimates
of operating profit for Macy's Christmas quarter or for the
company's fiscal year ended next July 31. One of them,
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. analyst Ray
Garea, cited "the softening retail environment."
   Even though Macy's bonds are as cheap as ever, Mr. Garea
said, his short-term outlook for the company has switched to
"negative" from neutral. Similarly, J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. analyst
Michael Cha said he is lowering his "worst-case" estimate of
Macy's Christmas quarter operating profit by more than 10%.
   As recently as last July, Macy's internal forecasts called
for 2% year-to-year growth in same-store sales for the six
months ending Jan. 31. But because of signs that retail sales
are slowing, Mr. Ullman said, Macy now expects flat
same-store sales in the period. Even that forecast may be
optimistic, he conceded.
   Mr. Ullman reiterated Macy's earlier forecast that
operating profit -- or profit before interest, taxes,
depreciation and amortization -- would total $654 million for
the six months ending next Jan. 31. He acknowledged that many
analysts regard that target as unachievable in the current
retailing slump.
   "Before the Kuwait invasion and the recession in the U.S.,
Macy was on target for a profit recovery," said Barrie
Littel, an analyst at First Boston Corp. "Now anyone
realistic has to trim their numbers."
   Last year, Macy turned in a disappointing $416 million
operating profit for the six months ended Jan. 31.
   Even if the Christmas selling season isn't much better
than last year's, Mr. Ullman said, Macy is controlling its
inventory more tightly and should show improved profit
margins. He also said Macy's reduced buying of merchandise is
leaving it with plenty of unused bank credit, which helps
build confidence among shippers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900919-0062
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900919-0062.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Top Leaders
   Take Over Talks
   To Cut Deficit
   ----
   By David Wessel and Jackie Calmes
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
PETROLEUM (PET)
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
INSURANCE (INS)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Top congressional leaders took over budget
negotiations with the White House, after lower-ranking
lawmakers failed to resolve the key remaining issues in
marathon bargaining.
   "The talks are not collapsed," House Republican Leader
Robert Michel said, after Democratic leaders and their GOP
counterparts met with top Bush administration negotiators.
"We are just moving them to a different stage."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators from both parties said they narrowed their
differences substantially during 11 days of closed-door talks
at Andrews Air Force Base near here. Indeed, the offers put
on the table late Monday have many common elements, such as a
new tax on luxury goods and a goal of $120 billion of
spending cuts in benefits programs over the next five years.
   But, as several people close to the talks have been
assuming for months, the final -- and most difficult -- calls
now must be made at the top ranks by Senate Democratic Leader
George Mitchell, House Speaker Thomas Foley (D., Mich.) and
President Bush himself.
   Democrats insist that the major stumbling block to the
long-sought accord to reduce the federal budget deficit is
the administration's desire to cut the capital-gains tax rate
without also raising income tax rates on wealthier Americans.
"The problem . . . centers around the insistence of the
administration to reduce the capital-gains tax, " Rep. Foley
said.
   Republicans, while sensitive to Democrats' criticism that
the capital-gains cut is a break for the rich, emphasized
that other major issues remain, including the rules by which
a five-year fiscal blueprint will be enforced and the details
of spending cuts. "To suggest that we were very close, except
for that {capital-gains taxes}, was exceptionally
inaccurate," a Republican participant said.
   With only 12 days left before across-the-board spending
cuts are imposed by the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law,
Sen. Mitchell of Maine and Rep. Foley are to meet again today
with White House Budget Director Richard Darman, Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady and White House Chief of Staff John
Sununu. Also participating will be the top Republican
leaders, Sen. Robert Dole of Kansas and Illinois Rep. Michel,
as well as House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt of
Missouri.
   Excluded will be some negotiators with particularly
inveterate views, including Sen. Robert Byrd (D., W.Va.),
Sen. James Sasser (D., Tenn.), Sen. Phil Gramm (R., Texas)
and Rep. Newt Gingrich (R., Ga.).
   Even if the high-level talks produce an accord, however,
ratification by the full Congress isn't guaranteed. Just
yesterday, Democrats on the Ways and Means Committee
privately complained to Chairman Dan Rostenkowski (D., Ill.)
that budget negotiators weren't testing their proposals
sufficiently with their colleagues, and warned that a
deficit-reduction package might be rejected as a result.
   Speaking to reporters aboard Air Force One, Mr. Bush said,
"Everybody . . . agrees that they've come quite a way, but
it's not done, by a long shot." He avoided any criticism of
Democrats in campaign speeches yesterday, but reiterated his
eagerness to cut capital-gains taxes. "This is not a tax
break for the rich," he said in Denver. "It will create
jobs."
   In a sixth round of proposals, Democrats and Republicans
on Monday night traded stripped-down plans that were crafted
as much for public consumption as for each party. Democrats
said they would give up most of their spending and tax
initiatives if Republicans gave up the quest for lower
capital-gains taxes. Both proposals would reduce the deficit
by about $50 billion in fiscal 1991, which begins Oct. 1, and
by about $500 billion over five years.
   On taxes, the basic division is how to offset a cut in the
capital-gains tax rate. Democrats proposed a 20% income-tax
surcharge on couples with incomes of more than $200,000 and
individuals with incomes above $125,000, effectively raising
their marginal tax rate to 33.6% from the current top nominal
rate of 28%.
   Republicans concede that any compromise will have to raise
taxes on the rich and have offered several alternatives,
including limiting total tax deductions for upper-income
taxpayers. Their last offer was to limit to $10,000 the
deduction for state and local income taxes for taxpayers with
incomes above $200,000.
   Several Republicans complained privately that Sen.
Mitchell, long a proponent of higher tax rates on the rich,
was standing in the way of a compromise.
   Though both parties would raise taxes by a net of $130
billion over five years, Democrats propose additional tax
increases to cover expanded proposed tax breaks for
lower-income taxpayers, as well as a variety of user fees
they didn't count as taxes. "The Democratic package has too
many taxes in it," Sen. Pete Domenici (R., N.M.), a
negotiator, said.
   In a previously undisclosed area of agreement on taxes,
both parties proposed to forbid corporations from deducting
interest on tax underpayments, raising about $4.5 billion
next year. The two parties also agreed to increase taxes on
life insurance companies by $2 billion in the first year and
by $10 billion over five years.
   Both parties endorsed a new 10% tax on luxury goods, to be
applied to the purchase price in excess of $30,000 for cars,
boats and yachts; $5,000 for jewelry; $1,000 for electronics;
$500 for furs and the entire price of private aircraft under
5,000 pounds. And both parties support an increase in taxes
on liquor, beer and wine, to yield about $14 billion over
five years, though the details weren't described in the
proposals.
   Democrats proposed increasing the tobacco tax, now 16
cents on a pack of cigarettes, by four cents a pack in 1991
and an additional four cents in 1993. Though Democrats said
Republicans have tentatively agreed, several Republicans deny
this -- and their proposal doesn't show any such increase.
   Though both sides would raise energy taxes, the Democrats
would raise $49 billion over five years through higher energy
taxes. The Republicans, who would limit increased energy
taxes to refined petroleum products, would raise $7 billion.
   On defense spending, both parties are converging on a plan
crafted by Sen. Sam Nunn (D., Ga.), chairman of the Armed
Services Committee. The administration estimates the plan
would reduce projected Pentagon spending by about $175
billion over five years; some Democrats say it would save
even more. In what remains an important sticking point,
however, Democrats are willing to lock in the defense cuts
for only the next two years, while Republicans want to set
totals for the next five years.
   Democrats, in short, want to leave open the possibility of
tapping the defense budget to fund domestic spending programs
in future years, while Republicans want to limit increases in
domestic spending, other than benefit or entitlement
programs, to the rate of inflation.
   On benefit programs, both parties said they want to cut
projected spending by about $120 billion over five years,
though Republicans said the Democrats' proposals fall short
of that mark. Neither plan would touch Social Security
benefits.
   In the latest proposals, Republicans proposed deeper cuts
in Medicare, calling for, among other things, increasing the
deductible on coverage for doctors' services, known as Part
B, to $150 from the current $75 and increasing the deductible
with inflation. They would raise the premium for Medicare,
now at $28.60 a month, so that the premium covers 30% of the
total costs instead of 25%, as the law now provides. Details
of the Democratic plan weren't available.
   Both parties also proposed substantial cuts in farm
subsidies over five years. Democrats would reduce them by
$11.8 billion from levels projected in the farm bill that has
passed both houses of Congress. Republicans would reduce
subsidies by $13.3 billion. Sponsors of the farm bill
explicitly delayed making any substantial cutbacks in
subsidies, pending the outcome of the budget summit.
   As they have from the start, the Republicans pushed for a
substantially tougher revision of the Gramm-Rudman law than
Democrats are prepared to accept to enforce the terms of any
budget accord. "Their current enforcement {plan} is, `Trust
me.'" Rep. Gingrich complained.
   With the White House forecasting a fiscal 1991 deficit of
about $250 billion, neither Democrats nor Republicans would
try to meet the law's $64 billion deficit target; rather,
they are expected to amend the law to avoid triggering
across-the-board spending cuts.
   Without any change in the law, spending cuts amounting to
more than $85 billion will be triggered on Oct. 1. Though
there is substantial skepticism in Congress, the
administration vows it won't agree to waive the law unless
there is a budget agreement.
   "The clock is ticking," Mr. Bush said.
   ---
   Jeffrey H. Birnbaum and Michel McQueen contributed to this
article.
   ---
                    The Budget Process
                                                                                                       

                Where the Negotiators Agree
                                                                                                       

   -- Raise taxes by about $130 billion net over five years,
including:
       New 10% tax on luxury goods
       Higher taxes on liquor, beer and wine
       Increase in energy taxes
       New tax on ozone-depleting chemicals
                                                                                                       

   -- Cut projected spending on benefit programs by about
$120 billion over five years.
                                                                                                       

   -- Hold increase in domestic spending next year to no more
than the rate of inflation.
                                                                                                       

                    Where They Disagree
                                                                                                       

   -- How to raise taxes on the rich to offset cut in
capital-gains taxes.
                                                                                                       

   -- Whether to increase tax breaks for low-income
Americans.
                                                                                                       


                                                                                                       

   -- How much to cut Medicare spending.
                                                                                                       

   -- How to enforce the five-year agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900919-0061
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900919-0061.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Are Supermarket Aisles
   A Haven From Recession?
   ----
   By Roger Lowenstein
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   GAP SWY GFSA ABS KR VON SNF ASC
</CO>
<IN>
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Salomon Brothers is putting out the word: "Now
is the time to buy supermarket stocks."
   Salomon's thinking, and that of Wall Street generally, is
that even in a recession, people keep on eating. But this
time the stocks aren't cheap. Going into the early-80s
recession, shares of the major supermarket chains traded at
about eight times earnings. Now they trade at about 19 times
the past year's per-share earnings, meaning that the market
is betting on growth even as a recession looms.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   And as anyone who shops for groceries knows, the
supermarket of today doesn't resemble the one of 10 years ago
-- and therein lies a reason for investors to be wary.
   What's on the shelves nowadays isn't as indispensable as
in the past. In the prosperous 1980s, supermarkets added
scores of fresh and prepared foods to the traditional array
of canned and packaged goods, and profit margins exploded.
Great Atlantic &amp; Pacific Tea's gross margin on sales, for
instance, surged to about 25% from 22%.
   Where it once offered 125 items of produce, A&amp;P now sells
300 fruits and vegetables -- including, says Michael Rourke,
a spokesman, "things I hadn't heard of before."
   A&amp;P's customers are spending at its new fresh seafood
counters, and at its bakeries and delicatessens and at
counters stocked with freshly prepared, ready-to-serve
gourmet foods.
   And, to take another example, at rapidly modernizing
Safeway, margins have soared by nearly two percentage points
since 1987 as the chain has introduced everything from live
lobster to takeout food prepared in Safeway's "complete
Chinese kitchens."
   Thus, the question isn't whether people will continue to
get their three squares. It is, to quote Mr. Rourke: "Will
they keep eating fresh seafood or switch because it's too
expensive? Will they quit buying prepared foods?
   "This is a question we have discussed quite a bit and we
don't know the answer," Mr. Rourke says. The period in which
the industry revamped itself coincided with "eight years of
good times."
   The answer is critical -- and not just for A&amp;P. According
to Salomon's Debra Levin, many newer stores garner as much as
50% of sales from "perimeter" departments such as delis,
bakeries, expanded produce, meat, seafood, floral sections
and pharmacies.
   The gross margin is 35% to 40% on fresh fish, store-baked
breads, produce and homemade chicken salad. The margin on
canned soup is 15% to 20%; on packaged breads, 10% to 15%. (A
store that sells for $1 an item costing it 90 cents has a 10%
gross margin).
   And with the advent of tough times in the Northeast, A&amp;P
says its sales growth has slowed. "The general economy has
slowed down," Mr. Rourke says. "People are watching what they
spend."
   Giant Food, the dominant chain in Washington, D.C., also
may be losing steam, says Oppenheimer's Edward Comeau.
Giant's gross margins, at 30%, are said to be the industry's
highest. Yet Giant's sales growth at stores open more than a
year has tailed off to a paltry 2.1% in the first half of
1990, after roaring ahead at about a 7% rate for three years.
David Sykes, chief financial officer, cites the downbeat
local economy and adds: "We haven't seen any shift in buying
patterns, but we may. People may be going where the specials
are."
   Many analysts expect supermarkets to hang on to a good
chunk of their newer, high-profit business no matter how the
economy fares. Prepared foods appeal to the two-income
families where no one has time to slice and dice. Fresh
vegetables and fish have become a staple for health-conscious
Americans who measure the actuarial effect of every bite.
   Then, too, the percentage of disposable personal income
that Americans spend on eating at home has shrunk steadily,
to 7.3% today from 14.1% in 1960, according to the U.S.
Department of Labor. Some analysts predict that consumers who
need to tighten their belts are unlikely to do so at the
supermarket. But their view is certainly debatable: If one's
spouse is out of work, grilled cheese tastes awfully good.
Supermarkets are full of shoppers wheeling down the aisles,
squinting at price labels to save a few pennies per item.
   Although grocers have fared better than other industries
in past recessions, they haven't been immune. Typically, they
find it harder to raise prices, and thus, harder to maintain
margins. "Our best guess is we're reasonably
recession-resistant," says Patrick Totman, Safeway senior
vice president. "I don't think anyone is truly
recession-proof."
   But the market is expecting supermarkets to grow, not just
tread water. And if people aren't likely to skip meals in bad
times, it is also dubious that they will start eating more.
To grow, supermarkets either must steal market share from
other stores or become more efficient.
   Supermarket analysts know this, and profess not to be
worried. They are bulls -- with fingers crossed. "Companies
Should Hold Up Well in Mild Recession" says a recent report
by Shearson Lehman's Kimberly Walin, a fan, among others, of
Albertson's and Kroger. Yet in her generally upbeat report, a
caveat draws the reader's eye: "The industry's change makes
direct comparisons with (earlier) recessions not totally
objective . . . If we were to enter a very sharp recession,
the industry's product mix evolution could make it a bit more
vulnerable."
   Sutro &amp; Co.'s Jonathan Ziegler also sees supermarkets as a
haven in rocky times. In a report touting Albertson's,
American Stores and Safeway, Mr. Ziegler gushes over the
modern supermarket's new look -- in his words, "the exciting
presentation in many markets." But his excitement
notwithstanding, he also notes that "in recent months,
same-store sales growth apparently has begun to slow in
certain markets." He adds, almost as an afterthought: "We now
detect some signs that price competition may be reintroduced
on a selective basis . . . Thus, we have recently scaled back
our sales growth assumptions for the balance of this year."
(Late yesterday, American Stores announced it is exploring
the sale of Acme Markets, its 275-store East Coast unit.)
   If a recession does take hold, Mr. Ziegler and others
argue that stores should see an increase in customer traffic,
because people would avoid restaurants and eat more often at
home. Safeway's Mr. Totman expects that while a downturn
might lead some high-margin Safeway shoppers to switch to
frozen dinners, "other people who are dining in Chinese
restaurants will buy (Safeway's) takeout Chinese food."
   Not all of the supermarket industry's improvement in the
'80s can be attributed to high-profit foods. Its warehousing
and distribution practices have become highly computerized.
In terms of technology, "supermarkets are so far ahead of the
rest of retailing it's frightening," says Mary McAboy, head
of industrial relations at Von's. That trend is pushing more
of gross profits to the bottom line. Thus, any
recession-induced damage may be small.
   But because supermarkets' net income is only about 1% of
sales, small changes in operations have a way of looking
large. And high multiples give the industry little room for
faltering.
   Oppenheimer's Mr. Comeau says Albertson's, growing at 20%
to 25% a year, could slip in a down economy "to the 13% to
15% level." There is no complaint here with 15% growth. But
with Albertson's -- to cite an example -- trading at 20 times
the past 12 months' earnings, the Street is expecting growth
to be superlative. In terms of its stock price, merely solid
growth mightn't be enough.
   ---
   Country fund fever has turned out to be a killer. But it
may be creating some healthy buying opportunities.
   Late last year, frenzied buying shoved up the stocks of
publicly traded funds that invest in Austria, Germany,
Malaysia, Thailand and elsewhere. Buyers of fund shares, who
often paid $1.50 to buy a portfolio of stocks worth $1, now
are sitting on sickening losses.
   Nowhere have the losses been bigger than at Spain Fund,
which provoked the most extreme buying binge. Heavy Japanese
purchases at one point propelled the fund's stock to trade at
2.4 times the value of the fund's portfolio. But Spain Fund,
once quoted at 39, dropped yesterday to 10 7/8, a 52-week
low, before closing at 11. The fund's shares now are at a 14%
discount to the fund's $12.74 per-share portfolio value.
   For today's bottom fishers, country funds are "down to
realistic levels," says Richard Barone, chairman of
Cleveland's Maxus Investment Group. "They're now good buys
for the long-term investor."
   -- Jonathan Clements
</TEXT>
</DOC>
