<HL>
   Stotler Settles SEC Charges
   On Government Securities
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   SG
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commission said
that Stotler &amp; Co., a now-closed Chicago futures firm,
settled SEC charges of securities law violations in
connection with its government-securities business.
   Without admitting or denying any wrongdoing, Stotler
agreed to have its registration as a government-securities
brokerage firm revoked. The charges stem from Aug. 21, when
the SEC and Commodity Futures Trading Commission brought
action against the firm. Stotler settled the CFTC charges but
hadn't resolved the SEC matter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stotler is the futures-brokerage arm of Stotler Group
Inc., which was partly owned by former Chicago Board of Trade
Chairman Karsten Mahlmann. Mr. Mahlmann resigned his CBOT
post after another Stotler unit was charged by the CFTC with
making loans with customer funds from commodity pools.
   The SEC alleged that Stotler &amp; Co. failed to maintain
sufficient capital, failed to file documents and kept
outdated and improper records of capital levels and of
positions in the government-securities markets. The complaint
also charged that Stotler didn't notify the SEC that its net
capital was below the required minimum.
   Stotler Group filed a Chapter 7 bankruptcy petition in
federal bankruptcy court late last month.
   In Chicago, attorneys for Stotler &amp; Co. weren't available
for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900919-0051
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900919-0051.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Ford Canada Raises Offer
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   FC T.FMC F LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- The Canadian subsidiary of Ford Motor Co.
presented a new contract proposal offering more money in a
bid to end a four-day-old strike by about 13,000 unionized
employees.
   While calling the company's latest package a "serious"
offer, Robert White, president of the Canadian Auto Workers
union, said the proposal still fell short of many of the the
union's minimum demands in important areas such as wages,
additional holiday time, job security and fringe benefits.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The union leader appeared to back away from his earlier
threats to abandon the bargaining table, and he said
negotiations would continue in an effort to reach a contract
settlement.
   Ford has "obviously rejected a number of our bottom-line
proposals. We'll have to see if we can do anything about that
in the next couple of days," Mr. White said.
   Donald McKenzie, Ford Canada's chief negotiator, said the
company's latest offer was a "significant improvement" over
its first proposal made last week, which was swiftly rejected
by the union. The CAW has made clear it didn't dispute the
"direction" of the offer, but rather the amount of money put
on the table.
   "My sense is {the new offer} will move things forward
rapidly," Mr. McKenzie said. He wouldn't provide details of
the latest package.
   The strike by Ford Canada employees has shut nine of
Ford's plants in Canada and threatened to hobble operations
at some key Ford plants in the U.S.
</TEXT>
