<HL>
   Business Brief -- Itel Corp.:
   Company Buys Back 25%
   Of Shares Held by Henley
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   ITL HENG
</CO>
<IN>
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
INDUSTRIAL &amp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Itel Corp. repurchased 4,675,000 of its shares from Henley
Group Inc. last week at $18 a share, or about $84 million.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Henley said it now holds 14 million Itel shares, or 33% of
those outstanding.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In August, Itel, a leasing company, agreed to buy 25%, or
4,675,000 shares, of the 18.7 million shares that Henley
owned at $18 a share.
   Itel also agreed to buy another 4,675,000 shares held by
Henley before the end of the year for about $91 million, or
$19.50 a share.
   Itel has an option to buy the remaining 9,350,000 shares
that Henley owns at $21 a share if it makes the purchase by
March 31, 1991, or at $22 a share if it buys the stake by
July 31, 1991. If Itel doesn't exercise the option, it must
underwrite the sale of the 9,350,000 shares at $22 a share,
or $206 million, according to the pact.
   On Monday, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. downgraded its rating
on more than $1 billion of Itel debt, citing the increased
leverage prompted by Itel's agreement to buy back shares from
Henley. S&amp;P said the buy-back, which is being financed
through asset sales, will increase debt leverage during an
expected economic downturn.
</TEXT>
