<HL>
   Former CIA Agent Clines
   Convicted of 4 Tax Charges
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B10
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES MDEST LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   BALTIMORE -- A former CIA agent who procured arms as part
of the secret Iran-Contra network supporting the Nicaraguan
rebels was convicted of four tax charges.
   Thomas Clines was found guilty yesterday by a jury in
federal court in Baltimore of making false statements on tax
returns to hide his arms-dealing profits in the Iran-Contra
affair. The jury deliberated for about three hours before
convicting Mr. Clines on all four counts in the indictment.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Clines, whom prosecutors had portrayed as a central
figure in the Contra arms deals, is scheduled to be sentenced
Oct. 31. He faces a maximum prison term of 16 years and as
much as $1 million in fines.
   His lawyer attempted unsuccessfully during the 10-day
trial to portray her client's tax return misstatements and
omissions as minor and at worst, negligent, not criminal.
