<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
09/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE U.S. BOOSTED its estimate of Iraqi troop strength in
and around Kuwait.
   The Pentagon said Baghdad has 360,000 troops and 2,800
tanks in Kuwait and nearby areas of Iraq, showing a steady
increase, but the forces still appear to be in a defensive
position. Meanwhile, Washington reproached Jordan for playing
host to a meeting of Arab radicals, and Bush said Iraq's
military mustn't benefit from any humanitarian aid shipments.
In Paris, nine European nations demanded that the U.N. trade
embargo on Iraq be extended to the air as well as the sea.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sailors stopped and boarded a Soviet ship headed for
Jordan, and let the vessel proceed after determining that the
cargo wasn't bound for Iraq.
   ---
   THE PENTAGON SAID it will eliminate or reduce operations
at 150 foreign sites.
   The cutbacks at the mostly small foreign facilities in 10
nations, mainly in Europe, are designed to carry out pledges
to shrink the size of the armed forces in response to budget
cuts, and to meet force reductions that will be required in
Europe under the conventional arms control treaty expected to
be signed in November. Defense officials said the closings,
to take place over several years, aren't linked to the U.S.
troop buildup in Saudi Arabia.
   The announcement is certain to be welcomed in Moscow,
which is pulling all its troops out of Europe and had pressed
the U.S. to state its intentions.
   ---
   South Africa said it will charge Winnie Mandela, wife of
African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela, with
kidnapping and assault. The charges involve the alleged 1988
abduction and beating of four young men, one of whom was
found dead. Her bodyguard was sentenced to death in the case;
Mrs. Mandela has denied wrongdoing.
                                                                                                       

   The ANC began an emergency meeting on township wars that
have killed 760 people in five weeks. The anti-apartheid
group has accused security forces of waging war on its people
by siding with the Zulu-based Inkatha movement in factional
fighting.
   ---
   Ryzhkov told the Soviet national legislature he would
resign as prime minister if the lawmakers adopted a 500-day
plan to create a free market. During a debate in the
542-member Supreme Soviet, legislators attacked all three
economic programs that had been proposed in the past week.
                                                                                                       

   Solzhenitsyn urged a populist revival of democracy and
spirituality in Russia without Western cultural "garbage" or
capitalist exploitation. In a Soviet newspaper article, the
exiled Nobel laureate wrote of his desire for a unified
Slavic nation.
   ---
   Atlanta was awarded the 1996 Summer Games by the
International Olympic Committee, a move that could generate
as much as $3.5 billion in revenue and 84,000 jobs for the
local and state economy. City officials estimate they will
have to spend more than $400 million to construct Olympic
facilities.
   ---
   The EPA said nine major companies have agreed to
substantially reduce emissions of toxic chemicals at 40
plants in 14 states. EPA chief Reilly also said the agency is
issuing a guidebook on asbestos emphasizing that removal
isn't necessarily the best way to reduce potential exposure.
   ---
   Poland's Jaruzelski announced his intention to resign the
presidency early and clear the way for free elections to make
Poland a full democracy. Parliament is to meet tomorrow to
debate the timing of Jaruzelski's resignation and the
scheduling of elections.
   ---
   Shamir contended that the U.S. isn't doing enough to
broker peace between Israel and its Arab neighbors. The
Israeli prime minister said that ending his nation's state of
war with Arab countries took precedence over reaching an
agreement with the Palestinians under Israeli rule.
   ---
   The U.S. is prepared to give up its bases in the
Philippines but wants a decision delayed until the next
century, chief American negotiator Richard Armitage said as
talks opened in Manila regarding the future of the U.S.-run
military facilities.
   ---
   Liberal opposition to Souter was less than expected as
confirmation hearings for the Supreme Court nominee neared
completion. Most of the testimony against Souter at the
Senate Judiciary Committee hearings came from abortion-rights
groups and women's rights advocates.
   ---
   The House voted to reduce spending for the Strategic
Defense Initiative to $2.3 billion in fiscal 1991 -- the
lowest level in more than five years and nearly half of the
Bush administration's request for the program.
   ---
   The U.S. extended for another year a longstanding trade
embargo against Vietnam, a Treasury Department spokesman
said. The action was expected to disappoint Hanoi officials,
who had been hoping that a new dialogue with the U.S. and
progress toward peace in Cambodia would prompt Washington to
lift the embargo.
   ---
   "Miss Saigon" will open on Broadway in April, after being
canceled because of a dispute with New York actors over plans
to cast a white British actor in a Eurasian role. Cameron
Mackintosh, the London musical's producer, and Actors' Equity
officials didn't provide details of their accord.
   ---
   Bulgaria banned food exports in an effort to improve
domestic supplies in time for winter. Sugar, cheese, cooking
oil and detergent have been rationed since late summer in
most parts of Bulgaria as the government attempts to
alleviate shortages.
   ---
   The Salvadoran government ended a second round of
fruitless negotiations with guerrillas as peace prospects
dimmed. During six days of talks in Costa Rica, the two sides
were unable to reach an accord on the future role of El
Salvador's armed forces.
   ---
   A top State Department official flew to Monrovia on a
fact-finding mission and met with Liberian rebel leader
Prince Johnson. Herman Cohen, assistant secretary of state
for African affairs, said he hoped to meet later with rival
guerrilla leader Charles Taylor to discuss the nation's civil
war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
